It isn't the way it should be. The C API exposes Z3_is_string and Z3_get_string. 
They seem not leveraged in the .Net or Java APIs yet. This is a bug.

to test for str.len it is more robust to roll a version for:

boolean isSeqLen()
{
     return isApp() && getFuncDecl()..getDeclKind() == Z3_decl_kind.Z3_SEQ_LENGTH;
}

(see Expr.java for examples).

In Z3 strings are special cases of sequences.

If your function is just a macro, then the approach over the API is to define an expression builder that returns the body of the function given expressions that represent the arguments. 
For example 
 
expr mk_valid_stack(expr& a, expr& s, expr& stack) {
    return (a + s) <= stack;
}

(I believe we have the appropriate overloads available to write it like this).

Note also that your aximatization of valid_stack is not correct.
You need 

(assert (forall ((a Int) (s Int)) (= (valid_stack a s) (<= (+ a s) stack)))))

Z3 should detect that this is a macro. and compile every occurrence of (valid_stack a s) into the definition.

@willard-yuan Thank you for letting me know. I had seen that repository previously, but not close enough to see that he provides the VGG 19 pre-trained model alongside the project.
After opening this issue, I found out about @kastnerkyle's **sklearn-theano** which I have been using since then. Fortunately, there have been great progress since then regarding access to pre-trained models. At the moment, in addition to the sklearn-theano, Lasagne provides some of the most used Caffe pre-trained models. Also there is a (not-yet-merged) branch in Keras to add support for importing pre-trained Caffe models. However, due to recent substantial changes in Keras' API, I don't think it would be merged in the near future. 
It's also worth mentioning that there is [theano-alexnet](https://github.com/uoguelph-mlrg/theano_alexnet). It's a pure Theano implementation of the AlexNet model along with the weights. So one can also take a look at this, too. So far I can say that this is the only model created with Theano that has actually **been trained** on the ImageNet dataset.

