Yeah, after digging some more in pyreadline code, I discovered some internal private methods I can user to alter the redraw, which seems to got me to point of "ugly but working as desired"
ended up doing this:

(pyinstaller was a typo, I meant pyreadline, dealing with too many things at once)

```python
    def poutput(self, msg, end='\n'):
        try:
            if hasattr(readline.rl,"prompt_begin_pos"):
                readline.rl._update_prompt_pos(-1)
            if self.active_prompt:
                line_buff = readline.get_line_buffer()
                if line_buff and line_buff[-1] == '\n':
                    line_buff = ""
                reprint = '%s%s' % (self.active_prompt or "", line_buff)
                reprint.rstrip('\n')
                self.stdout.write('\r'+' ' * (len(reprint)+2)+'\r')
                Cmd.poutput(self, msg, end=end)
                if hasattr(readline.rl,"prompt_begin_pos"):
                    readline.rl._update_line();
                else:
                    self.stdout.write(reprint)
            else:
                Cmd.poutput(self, msg, end=end)
        except Exception,ex:
            print "Exception: %s" % ex

    def pseudo_raw_input(self, prompt):
        self.active_prompt = prompt
        line = Cmd.pseudo_raw_input(self, prompt)
        self.active_prompt = None
        return line
```

I'm not sure about that fix. It may not be covered by the tests, but the forwarded policy is probably useful for higher-order functions, e.g. `m.def("foo", &foo, some_policy)` where `foo()` returns a `std::function<...>` and so `some_policy` doesn't apply to `foo` itself but is forwarded to the returned function. @wjakob Was this the intent behind the `std::function` caster?

In general, this line:
```c++
m.attr("func") = func;
```
can be replaced with any of the following lines to get the desired effect:
```c++
// alt 1
m.def("func", func);
// alt 2
m.attr("func") = py::cpp_function(func);
// alt 3
m.attr("func") = py::cast(func, py::return_value_policy::take_ownership);
```

